Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# Define function to draw histogram and boxplot
# We use the function to visualize different parameters without repeating the code
def draw_hist_box(data, param):
  '''Draw histogram and boxplot of a parameter param from data'''
  if param in data.columns:
    param_title = param.replace('_', ' ').title() # Format param name to use as title

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

    # Histogram
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1) # Drawing histogram on upper subplot
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=param, kde=True)
    plt.title('Histogram of '+param_title)
    plt.xlabel("")

    # Boxplot
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 2) # Drawing boxplot on lower subplot
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=param)
    plt.title('Boxplot of '+param_title)
    plt.xlabel("")

    plt.tight_layout() # Adjusts subplot parameters for a tight layout.
    plt.show()
  else:
    print(f"Column '{param}' not found in the DataFrame.")

# Function to plot relationship boxplots between x and y, including the means.
# The boxplot shows the median and IQR of variable. We also add the mean value
# as a red circle to add more information about the variable.
# Adding hue to the graph is optional.
# We'll use this function to show relationships between different variables.

def relationship(x, y, data, hue=''):
  '''Draw relationship boxplots between x and y, including the means. hue is optional'''

  if x in data.columns and y in data.columns: # make sure x,y are in the dataframe
    # Define plot size
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))

    # Create the boxplot. Add hue if specified in input
    if hue in data.columns:
      ax = sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, data=data, hue=hue)
    else:
      ax = sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, data=data)

    # Format variable names to use in labels
    x_title = x.replace('_', ' ').title()
    y_title = y.replace('_', ' ').title()
    plt.title(f"Relationship between '{x}' and '{y}'")
    plt.xlabel(x_title)
    plt.ylabel(y_title)

    # Calculate and add the mean for each x value
    x_values = data[x].dropna().unique() # list of all non-NaN unique values
    for x_val in x_values:
        mean_value = data[data[x] == x_val][y].mean()
        ax.plot(np.where(x_values == x_val)[0], [mean_value], marker='o', color='red', markersize=8)

    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability if labels are too long
    max_label_length = max([len(str(label)) for label in x_values])
    if max_label_length > 100/len(x_values):
      plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

  else:
    print(f"Column '{x}' or '{y}' not found in the DataFrame.")

# Calculate which restaurants has recurring customers - customers who order more than once

# 1. Group df by restaurant and customer_id and get the count of the pair restaurant/customer
customer_restaurant_counts = df.groupby(['restaurant_name', 'customer_id'])['order_id'].count().reset_index()
# 2. The count of order_id's is the number of orders for each restaurat/customer
customer_restaurant_counts.rename(columns={'order_id': 'orders_count'}, inplace=True)
# 3. Remove rows with number of orders_count < 2
customer_restaurant_counts = customer_restaurant_counts[customer_restaurant_counts['orders_count'] > 1].reset_index(drop=True)
# 4. Group by restaurant name and count customers
recur_customers = customer_restaurant_counts.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['customer_id'].count().sort_values(ascending = False).reset_index()

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [204]:
# 1. Function to determine the revenue according to cost
def get_rev(x):
    if x > 20:
        return x*0.25
    elif x > 5:
        return x*0.15
    else:
        return 0

# 2. Apply the function get_rev on the column 'cost_of_the_order'
df['Revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(get_rev)

  • Most food orders are on weekends.

  • Order price is mostly around 12-22 dollars, with median at ~14 dollars and mean at ~17$.

  • Most costumers give good ratings (4-5), but 38% of the data is missing rating score.

  • The top 5 restauarnts (by number of orders) are: Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken and Parm. These restaurants has also many recurring customers.

  • The top-5 restaurants serve Americam, Italian and Japanese cuisines.

  • Restaurants with most high ratings are serving American, Italian and Japanese cuisines.

  • French and Thai cuisines are the most expensive and gives more revenue per order to the company.

  • Delivery time in weekdays takes longer than in weekends.

Recommendations:¶

  • Most orders are in weekends, also delivery time in weekend is shorter (probably because less traffic). It's recommended to get more restaurants that receive orders on weekends.
  • Find more restaurants that serve American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese cuisines. These are the most popular and have higher ratings.
  • Get also more French and Thai restaurants. Their food prices drives more revenue to the company.
  • Try to get more customer ratings by asking for reviews after order or giving incentives.
